  "prompt": "What is demographic dividend?",
  "response": "Demographic dividend refers to the potential economic growth and development that can occur when a country has a large working-age population relative to its dependent population (children and elderly). Here are key points about demographic dividend:\n\n1. Population Structure\n- A country experiences demographic dividend when working-age population (15-64 years) is significantly larger than dependent population\n- This creates a favorable age structure for economic growth\n\n2. Key Characteristics\n- Higher proportion of working-age people\n- Declining fertility rates\n- Reduced dependency ratio\n- Increased potential labor force\n\n3. Economic Benefits\n- Increased labor productivity\n- Higher savings and investment rates\n- Potential for accelerated economic growth\n- Improved per capita income\n\n4. Preconditions\n- Investments in human capital (education and skills)\n- Job creation\n- Sound economic policies\n- Healthcare improvements\n\n5. Time-Bound Opportunity\n- Demographic dividend is temporary\n- Typically lasts for 30-50 years\n- Requires strategic planning and policy interventions\n\n6. Examples\n- Countries like India, China, and many Southeast Asian nations have experienced or are experiencing demographic dividend\n\n7. Challenges\n- Need for adequate job opportunities\n- Skills development\n- Effective economic policies\n\nProper utilization of demographic dividend can significantly boost economic development.",
